Introduction to open data science

A short description

Introduction to open data science is a course about the tools, methods and best practices of scientific research and I suppose research in general using data science and open sources. I expect to practice my skill in R and get to know how to use Github and R Markdown, which seem like valuable tools for this purpose.

https://jknyemy.github.io/IODS-project/

Chapter 2

Chapter three

Of students and alcohol

For the purposes of this analysis, I will be comparing the high use of alcohol with four other variables. High use of alcohol is binary variable, where the variable is true, if mean of the students own estimate for their weekday and weekend alcohol use is over 2 on a scale of 1 to 5.

First of all, the students sex is worth looking at as an extra information:

studen_alc <- read.csv2("C:/Users/Janne/Documents/GitHub/IODS-project/data/student_alc.csv")
sukup <- table(studen_alc$sex, studen_alc$high_use)
plot(sukup, main = ("Alcohol usage by sex"), col=c("darkblue", "red"))

Of this we can surmise, that while there is a higher incidence of high alcohol consumption among males, there is still ample use among the females, but only one in four females fall under high use, while in males this proportion is two out five.

Free time and alcohol consumption

The connecting substance of the chosen variables is that they describe the students activities outside of studying, which one might assume is when most alcohol consumption takes place. On the other hand, lack of free time could drive a person towards stress induced intoxication as well. All in all, there were many variables to consider, for example travel time to school, but these four describe some basic components of free time.

First of all romance. I chose this variable to find out, whether a romantic commitment lessens the occurence of high alcohol use.

rom_alc <- table(studen_alc$high_use, studen_alc$romantic)
barplot(rom_alc, col=c("darkblue", "red" ), legend = rownames(studen_alc$romantic), main=("Romantic ties and alcohol"))

Chapter 4

Housing values in the Suburbs of Boston

The Boston dataset in the MASS package details the different conditions in 506 Boston suburbs through 14 variables ranging from per capita crime rate to access to highways and distance to employment centres and other variables relating to a suburbs attributes as a place to live. Here is a basic rundown of the general properties of the variables:

It needs to be pointed out that chas is a binomial variable, telling whether the area in question is on the Charles River. Next, a correlation matrix of the variables, where blue indicates a positive and red a negative correlation between variables(where the depth of the colour and the size of the ball indicates the strength of the correlation):

#Making a correlation matrix of variables
cor_matrix<-cor(Boston) %>% round(digits = 2)
corrplot(cor_matrix, method="circle", type = "upper", cl.pos = "b", tl.pos = "d", tl.cex = 0.6)

Here, for example we can see that there is some correlation between per capita crime rate(crim) and the ratio of non-retail businesses in a suburb(indus) and also with nitrogen oxide concentration levels in the air(nox). And a strong negative correlation between ages of the building(age) and distance to employment centres(dis), which would imply that the higher the age of the building, the nearer it is to employment. Also, there is a positive correlation between crime rate and age of the buidings. All of these are to be expected of a city that has grown outside from a city(or colonial town) centre, as Boston has.

In the following are the boxplots of the variables, omitting the variable chas, which is a binomial variable. As can be seen from the summary numbers earlier, the different distributions of variables are in very different scales, so to allow comparison, the data has been scaled to the standard normal distribution:

#Standardizing the Boston dataset
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)
boston_scaled <- as.data.frame(boston_scaled)
#Making the boxplots
bosvar1 <- c("indus", "lstat", "medv", "rad","crim", "dis")
bosvar2 <- c("black", "tax", "age", "rm","ptratio", "zn", "nox")
boston_m1 <- select(boston_scaled, one_of(bosvar1))
boxplot(boston_m1)

boston_m2 <- select(boston_scaled, one_of(bosvar2))
boxplot(boston_m2)

As can be observed, the distributions are quite varied, with for example the proportion of african-american population being quite densely gathered above the mean, but having lots of outliers with smaller proportions, the same applying to zn, which is the proportion of large residential lots, where the mass of the distribution is gathered around the mean, with outliers having larger proportions. However, these outliers dont matter much, which can be seen for example that the variable black is still skewed above the mean.

#Evolving the crim variable into a categorical variable by quantiles
scaled_crim <- boston_scaled$crim
bins <- quantile(scaled_crim)
crime_cat <- cut(scaled_crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
boston_scaled$crim <- crime_cat
#Producing a train set and a test set
n <- nrow(Boston)
ind <- sample(n,  size = n * 0.8)
train <- boston_scaled[ind,]
test <- boston_scaled[-ind,]
#Saving the crim variable from test and then removing it from it.
correct_classes <- test$crim
test <- dplyr::select(test, -crim)

Using linear discriminant analysis on the scaled data with crime rate as a target variable against the other variables and making a biplot of the results gives us the following:

#Fitting the linear discriminant analysis
lda.fit <- lda(crim ~ ., data = train)
#A function for arrows for the biplot
lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "orange", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
#A numeric vector to paint the picture by
classes <- as.numeric(train$crim)
#The biplot with arrows included
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch=classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 2)

From the biplot we can see, that high crime rate is clustered separately from the rest, but the rest, while overlapping, are still clustered so that on can discern the classes from it.The arrows show the impact of different variables on the model. While the presence of pollution(nox) and the rate of large properties(zn) have some impact, curiously it seems that in the case of high crime rate, the accessibility to radial highways(rad) has a very strong impact.

Next well see, how the model handles predicting.

#Prediction and a table of results
lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       13       9        2    0
##   med_low    3      19        5    0
##   med_high   0       4       20    3
##   high       0       0        0   24

As one can see, the predictions are very good when it comes to high crime rate, which was a very defined cluster on the biplot. Med high rate was quite cohesive as well and the prediction works somewhat well, giving the correct prediction 69% of the time. With both med_low and low, the predictions are 55% correct.

Next well se what sort of clusters are to be found from the standardized Boston dataset:

#Getting the euclidean distance matrix from scaled standardized values so they are comparable
data(Boston)
boston_rescale <- scale(Boston)
dist_bost <- dist(boston_rescale)
#Finding the optimal number of clusters
k_max <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(dist_bost, k)$tot.withinss})
plot(1:k_max, twcss, type='b')

As the function for within cluster sum of squares drops quite dramatically toeither two or four clusters, we will pick two, to see if there are some clear results. Next we will calculate the K-means, show a table of them and visualize the result:

km <-kmeans(dist_bost, centers = 2)
table(km$cluster)
## 
##   1   2 
## 179 327
pairs(boston_rescale, col = km$cluster)

So, dividing the observations into two clusters seems to yield some results and it seems that the clearest cluster is the one holding the variables for crime rate and the rate of the african american population. With three clusters the result is similar:

km <-kmeans(dist_bost, centers = 3)
table(km$cluster)
## 
##   1   2   3 
## 306  70 130
pairs(boston_rescale, col = km$cluster)

While the green cluster is somewhat mixed, the red cluster matches the black cluster from before. And the black cluster seems to hold the variables for rate of large sized lots and distance to employment centres which had a strong positive correlation. Interestingly, there was a medium sized negative correlation between crime rate and rate of african american population. The answer to this is not readily available from the work done now, but it is interesting.

Chapter 5

Varieties of development in the world

The following text analyses some variables taken from the UN Human Development Index. The eight variables chosen describe conditions relating to health, wealth, knowledge and the gender proportions in 155 countries of the world, where some countries are missing because of missing data from said countries. Here is a summary of the different variables:

Now, for example the variable Edu2.FM is the proportion of women having a secondary education divided by the proportion of men having the same. Labo.FM is the proportion of women in the labour force divided by the male proprtion. Interestingly the median values, which are perhaps more illuminating in this context, for the variables in question are quite high. The median of Edu2.FM is over 0.9. But the variance of the distribution is quite wide in these two variables, as it is in all variables. Now, observing the overview of the dataset and correlations between variables:

ggpairs(human)

corrplot(cor(human), type="upper")

Both of these visualizations seem to indicate a negative correlation between gross national income(GNI) on the other hand and maternal mortality rate and adolescence birth rate on the other hand. And a strong negative correlation between the rate of female education and both maternal mortality rate and adolescence birth rate. Interestingly, the correlation visualization suggests a weak positive correlation between womens participation in the labour force and no correlation at all between GNI and labour participation. From the scatterplots of the variables one can see, that labour participation is much more evenly distributed and one could indiuce from this, that very bad conditions often force people to work for sustenance even in situations, where it can have negative effects in child mortality for example.

Now the visualization of the analysis reveals that un-scaled variables offer little explanation, and the arrows signifying the impact of the variable in question are clumped together except for the GNI variable, which we have seen had a strong impact from the correlation plot above. However, scaling the variables to the same standardized scale might reveal more:

human_scaled <- scale(human)
pca_human_scaled <- prcomp(human_scaled)
biplot(pca_human_scaled, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.8, .8), 
       col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"))

Now this biplot seems to show more variation. The reason for this is, that when the variables were not scaled, many of them were not in comparable scales. For example, the ratios were mostly values between 0 and 1. The GNI in contrast varies from 581 to 123124, explaining its role in the unscaled analysis. So the variances are very different too. When the values are standardized, this problem is removed.

The plot shows that most western countries, as well as the majority of Asian countries are clumped to gether in the centre and on the left. Circling the clump containing most of the countries are several Middle-Eastern countries as well as countries from Sub-Saharan Africa, with some others, such as Bolivia. The variables impacting the spread, signified by the arrows show that the majority cluster (to use such an expression) is defined by Life Expectancy, Education and Wealth, where as the variables drawing countries to the right of the plot are Maternal Mortality and Adolescent Birth Rate and the variables drawing countries to the upper part are the Ratio of Women in Parliament as well as the rate of womens participation in the labour force. The lower part of the plot, containing many countries, has no arrows pointing there.

Tea

The tea dataset concerns the habits surrounding the consumption of tea, a popular beverage of Asian origin. It contains answers from 300 interviewees on 36 variables relating to their relationship to tea and some variables containing background information. I have chosen six variables concerning basic preferences in consumption of tea. Here are some visualizations of the data:

data(tea)

From this we can see, that the basic preferences between interviewees is clumped together quite closely, but when we observe the variables alone, we can see that such choices as whether Earl Grey -mix is used or whether one wants their tea black or sweet or lemony are the variables forming the cluster at the centre. Choices that can be seen as more sophisticated, such as the use of a tea shop and unpackaged tea are quite diffrentiated. This suggests that while the basic consumption patterns are factored closely together, the prefernce for example a tea shop and unpackaged tea are related.
